
Operating System (OS)
What if there were NO Operating System?

Without an OS, users would have to interact directly with hardware, making computer usage extremely difficult.

Problems without an OS
Bulky and Complex Applications
Every application would need to communicate directly with hardware devices.
Developers would have to write hardware-specific code.
Resource Exploitation
Programs could use all CPU, memory, and I/O resources without control.
No fair sharing of resources among applications.
No Memory Protection
One program could overwrite another program's memory.
System crashes would be very common.
No Security
Any program could access sensitive data or hardware directly.
Difficult Hardware Management
Users would need to know low-level hardware details to run programs.
Why Do We Need an Operating System?

The Operating System acts as a bridge between the user and the hardware.

Functions of OS
Acts as an Interface
Connects users/applications with hardware.
Resource Management
Manages CPU, memory, files, and I/O devices.
Hides Hardware Complexity
Users do not need to know hardware details.
Provides Security and Protection
Prevents unauthorized access to resources.
Provides a Convenient Environment
Allows users to execute programs easily.
Definition of Operating System

Operating System (OS) is a system software that manages all hardware and software resources of a computer system and provides an environment for users to execute programs conveniently while hiding the complexities of the underlying hardware.

Goals of an Operating System
1. Efficient CPU Utilization

The CPU is one of the most important resources and should not remain idle.

Example

Suppose there are two processes:

P1
P2

If P1 is currently executing and requests an I/O operation (disk access, keyboard input, etc.), it must wait.

Instead of keeping the CPU idle, the OS switches the CPU to P2.

This increases CPU utilization.

2. Fairness (Avoid Starvation)

Every process should eventually get CPU time.

Process Starvation

A process is said to be starving when it waits indefinitely because other processes continuously receive the required resources.

Example
P1 → High Priority
P2 → Medium Priority
P3 → Low Priority

If high-priority processes keep arriving, P3 may never execute.

This is called Process Starvation.

Solution

Aging

Gradually increase the priority of waiting processes.
Ensures every process eventually executes.
3. High Priority Execution

Important tasks should receive CPU time before less important tasks.

Examples:

Emergency system processes
Real-time applications
Interrupt handling

The OS must balance:

Fairness
Priority
CPU utilization
Types of Operating Systems
1. Single Program (Single Tasking) Operating System

A Single Program OS executes only one program at a time.

Working
Program 1 → Finish
             ↓
Program 2 → Finish
             ↓
Program 3 → Finish
Advantages
Simple design
Easy to implement
Disadvantages
Poor CPU Utilization
CPU remains idle during I/O operations.
Low Throughput
Fewer jobs completed per unit time.
No Multitasking
Only one program runs at a time.
High Waiting Time
Other programs must wait until the current one finishes.

Note: Starvation is usually not a major issue here because every process eventually gets executed in sequence.

Example

MS-DOS

2. Batch Processing Operating System

Batch OS executes a group (batch) of similar jobs together.

Definition

In a Batch Operating System, users do not interact directly with the computer during execution. Jobs are collected, grouped into batches, and executed one after another automatically.

Working
User Jobs
   ↓
Batch Queue
   ↓
Execution
   ↓
Output
Example
Payroll processing
Bank statement generation
Exam result processing
Advantages
Better CPU Utilization than Single Program OS.
Reduced setup time for similar jobs.
Efficient for large-scale repetitive tasks.
Disadvantages
No User Interaction During Execution.
Long Turnaround Time.
Difficult Debugging.
A job may wait a long time before execution.
Example

Suppose a college wants to generate results for 10,000 students.

Instead of processing each result separately, all result-generation jobs are collected and executed as one batch.
